const TEACH={
overview:{title:"Pediatric Limp — Evaluation Framework",patho:"Limp is an abnormality in gait caused by pain, weakness, or deformity. In toddlers, it may present as refusal to walk or stand. The hip and knee are the most common sites of pathology; minor trauma and transient synovitis predominate as the most frequent causes.\n\nMost children with limp have benign, self-limiting conditions. However, life- or limb-threatening conditions (septic arthritis, SCFE, osteomyelitis, malignancy, compartment syndrome) must be identified promptly. The location of pain does not always reflect the location of pathology — hip conditions can cause knee or thigh pain, abdominal conditions can cause hip pain, and back conditions can refer pain to the leg.",pearls:"Key evaluation principles:\n• Age drives the differential — think age-specific diagnoses first\n• Fever + joint pain = septic arthritis until proven otherwise\n• Always examine the hips even if the child complains of knee pain\n• An afebrile child with normal gait and normal exam may not need imaging at the initial visit\n• Children ≤3 years and those unable to walk warrant more thorough evaluation\n• Always consider NAT, especially in non-ambulatory children with fractures",evidence:"Fischer SU, Beattie TF. J Bone Joint Surg Br 1999; 81:1029 (epidemiology). Clark MC, Thompson A. Evaluation of limp in children. UpToDate 2025. Perry DC, Bruce C. BMJ 2010; 341:c4250."},
septicHip:{title:"Septic Hip — Emergency",patho:"Bacterial arthritis of the hip causes rapid joint destruction within hours due to proteolytic enzymes and increased intra-articular pressure compromising blood supply to the femoral head. S. aureus is the most common pathogen; Kingella kingae is increasingly recognized in children <5 years.\n\nThe hip joint is deeply seated, making clinical assessment challenging. A septic hip typically presents with the hip held in flexion, abduction, and external rotation to maximize joint volume and minimize pain. Any attempt at passive ROM causes severe pain.",pearls:"Emergency ultrasound is the key diagnostic step — it identifies effusion and can guide aspiration. A septic hip requires urgent surgical drainage.\n\nKocher criteria help differentiate septic arthritis from transient synovitis:\n• Fever (>38.5°C)\n• Non-weight-bearing\n• ESR >40 mm/hr\n• WBC >12,000/µL\n\n0 predictors: <0.2% risk · 1 predictor: 3% · 2 predictors: 40% · 3 predictors: 93% · 4 predictors: 99%\n\nCRP >2 mg/dL is now often added as a 5th predictor and may be more useful than ESR.",evidence:"Kocher MS et al. J Bone Joint Surg Am 1999; 81:1662 (original criteria). Caird MS et al. J Bone Joint Surg Am 2006; 88:1251 (added CRP). Sultan J, Hughes PJ. BMJ 2010; 341:c4250."},
transientSynovitis:{title:"Transient Synovitis",patho:"Transient (toxic) synovitis is the most common cause of acute hip pain in children aged 3–8 years. It is a self-limiting inflammatory condition, often following a viral upper respiratory infection. The hip has a small effusion on US but the child is generally well-appearing and can usually bear some weight.\n\nThe key clinical challenge is distinguishing transient synovitis from early septic arthritis. Transient synovitis resolves in 1–2 weeks with rest and NSAIDs.",pearls:"Features favoring transient synovitis over septic arthritis:\n• Age 3–8 years (peak incidence)\n• Afebrile or low-grade fever (<38.5°C)\n• Able to bear some weight (even if limping)\n• Recent URI (preceding 1–2 weeks)\n• Some ROM tolerated (painful at extremes)\n• Normal or mildly elevated inflammatory markers\n\nIf clinical picture is ambiguous: aspiration of the hip joint is the definitive differentiator. If synovitis suspected and markers low, outpatient follow-up in 24–48h with precautions is reasonable.",evidence:"Kocher MS et al. J Bone Joint Surg Am 1999; 81:1662. Luhmann SJ et al. J Pediatr Orthop 2004; 24:373 (CRP added)."},
scfe:{title:"Slipped Capital Femoral Epiphysis (SCFE)",patho:"SCFE is displacement of the femoral epiphysis posteriorly and inferiorly relative to the femoral neck through the physis. It occurs in the pre-pubertal or pubertal age group (typically 10–16 years) and is more common in obese children and those with endocrinopathies (hypothyroidism, growth hormone deficiency).\n\nThe slip disrupts the blood supply to the femoral head — weight-bearing on an unstable slip risks avascular necrosis. This is why immediate non-weight-bearing is mandatory.",pearls:"Classic presentation: obese adolescent with insidious hip or knee pain, antalgic gait, and obligate external rotation with hip flexion (decreased internal rotation on exam).\n\nCritical actions:\n• Immediate NON-WEIGHT-BEARING (crutches or wheelchair)\n• AP + frog-leg lateral of BILATERAL pelvis (not unilateral hip — a small slip can be missed without comparison)\n• Urgent orthopedic consultation for operative fixation\n\nDo not force internal rotation on exam — this can worsen the slip. Bilateral SCFE occurs in 20–40% of cases.",evidence:"Loder RT et al. J Bone Joint Surg Am 1993; 75:1134. Aronsson DD et al. J Am Acad Orthop Surg 2006; 14:666."},
toddlerFx:{title:"Toddler's Fracture",patho:"A toddler's fracture is a non-displaced spiral fracture of the tibial shaft that occurs in children typically aged 9 months to 3 years. It results from a low-energy twisting mechanism (catching foot while running, falling while held by the hand). The causative event may be unwitnessed or seem trivial.\n\nInitial radiographs may be normal — up to 20% of limping toddlers without localizing findings have occult fractures. Periosteal reaction becomes visible on repeat radiographs at 7–14 days.",pearls:"If clinical suspicion is high but radiographs are negative:\n• Immobilize (short leg splint, CAM boot, or short leg cast)\n• Follow-up in 7–10 days with repeat radiographs\n• If asymptomatic out of immobilization → discontinue without further imaging\n\nFor the non-localizable limp in a toddler: start with AP/lateral of tibia-fibula. Consider femur and foot radiographs if tibial films are normal. Always consider NAT if the mechanism is inconsistent with developmental stage.",evidence:"Oudjhane K et al. J Trauma 1988; 28:858 (up to 20% occult fractures). ACR Appropriateness Criteria: Acutely limping child up to age 5 (revised 2018)."},
malignancy:{title:"Malignancy — Red Flags",patho:"Leukemia is the most common malignancy presenting with limp in children. Bone pain from marrow infiltration may be the initial symptom. Osteosarcoma and Ewing sarcoma present with localized bone pain and swelling, typically in the metaphysis of long bones (distal femur, proximal tibia for osteosarcoma).\n\nNight pain and pain at rest that wakes the child from sleep are classic red flags for malignancy or benign bone tumors (osteoid osteoma).",pearls:"Red flags for malignancy in a limping child:\n• Night pain / pain at rest that wakes the child\n• Persistent bone pain without trauma\n• Systemic symptoms: fever, pallor, weight loss, fatigue, bruising\n• Hepatosplenomegaly or lymphadenopathy\n• Abnormal CBC (cytopenias, blasts)\n• Elevated LDH or uric acid\n\nLabs to obtain: CBC with differential + peripheral smear, ESR/CRP, LDH, alkaline phosphatase, uric acid. Plain radiographs of the painful area.\n\nSee the Hematologic Malignancy pathway for further workup if leukemia is suspected.",evidence:"Clark MC, Thompson A. UpToDate 2025. See also DCH Hematologic Malignancy pathway."},
gaitTypes:{title:"Gait Types and Their Significance",pearls:"Antalgic gait — Most common. Short stance phase on the affected side due to pain. Causes: fracture, infection, inflammation, tumor.\n\nTrendelenburg gait — Pelvic tilt toward unaffected side during swing phase. Suggests hip pathology: SCFE, Legg-Calvé-Perthes, DDH, JDM.\n\nToe-walking — Heel pain (Sever disease), calf pain (myositis), neurologic (cerebral palsy, tethered cord), or idiopathic.\n\nStooping gait — Hip flexed throughout gait cycle. Suggests psoas irritation: appendicitis, psoas abscess, PID, ovarian/testicular torsion.\n\nSteppage gait — Exaggerated hip/knee flexion to clear a dropped foot. Peroneal nerve injury, Charcot-Marie-Tooth.\n\nVaulting gait — Hyperextended knee, vaulting over the leg. Limb length discrepancy, JIA with knee involvement.",evidence:"Clark MC, Thompson A. UpToDate 2025, Table 2."},
imaging:{title:"Imaging Approach",pearls:"Localized pain → Plain radiographs (AP + lateral) of the painful site\n\nHip pain or knee pain with hip limitation → AP + frog-leg of BILATERAL pelvis (do NOT order unilateral hip — small SCFE can be missed)\n\nSuspected septic hip → Emergency ultrasound (bedside if available) → aspiration if effusion present\n\nNon-localizable limp in toddler → AP + lateral tibia-fibula first; consider femur and foot if normal\n\nNormal radiographs do NOT exclude: toddler's fracture, early osteomyelitis, septic arthritis, or early SCFE\n\nAdvanced imaging (MRI): consider for suspected osteomyelitis with negative radiographs, disc herniation, spinal pathology, stress fractures, or pyomyositis",evidence:"ACR Appropriateness Criteria: Acutely limping child up to age 5, revised 2018. Clark MC, Thompson A. UpToDate 2025."},
disposition:{title:"Disposition Guidance",pearls:"Emergent consult / admit:\n• Septic hip → OR for surgical drainage\n• SCFE → non-weight-bearing + urgent orthopedic fixation\n• Osteomyelitis → IV antibiotics + possible surgical debridement\n• Malignancy → staging workup + oncology\n• Compartment syndrome → emergency fasciotomy\n• NAT concerns → skeletal survey, social work, CPS\n\nOutpatient follow-up:\n• Suspected toddler's fracture (negative XR) → immobilize + reimage 7–10 days\n• Transient synovitis (low Kocher) → NSAIDs + follow-up 24–48h\n• Legg-Calvé-Perthes → orthopedic referral\n• JIA suspected → rheumatology referral\n\nDischarge with precautions:\n• Afebrile, normal radiographs, pain controlled with ibuprofen → PCP follow-up\n• Strict return precautions: worsening pain, fever, inability to bear weight, night pain, swelling",evidence:"Clark MC, Thompson A. UpToDate 2025. Perry DC, Bruce C. BMJ 2010."},
};

function calcDoses(w){var wt=parseFloat(w)||0;if(wt<=0)return null;return{w:wt,ibu:Math.round(wt*10),apap:Math.round(wt*15),ketorolac:Math.round(wt*0.5*10)/10,ketoMax:Math.min(Math.round(wt*0.5*10)/10,30),bolus:Math.round(wt*20),cefazolin:Math.round(wt*25),cefazolinMax:Math.min(Math.round(wt*25),1000),clinda:Math.round(wt*10),clindaMax:Math.min(Math.round(wt*10),600),vanc:Math.round(wt*15),nafcillin:Math.round(wt*50)};}

function useResponsive(){var s=useState(typeof window!=='undefined'?window.innerWidth:520),w=s[0],setW=s[1];useEffect(function(){var h=function(){setW(window.innerWidth)};window.addEventListener('resize',h);return function(){window.removeEventListener('resize',h)};},[]);return{maxW:w>=640?800:520};}

